<h2>Game Rules</h2>

<div class="card">
  <h3>Overview</h3>
  <p>
    Woodland War is an asymmetric strategy game for 2-4 players. Each player controls a unique faction 
    vying for control of the great woodland. The first player to score 30 victory points‚Äîor to 
    fulfill their dominance card condition‚Äîwins the game!
  </p>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h3>The Woodland</h3>
  <p>
    The game board represents a woodland divided into 12 clearings connected by paths. Each clearing 
    belongs to one of three suits: Fox, Rabbit, or Mouse. Clearings have building slots that limit 
    how many structures can be built there.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Paths:</strong> Connect clearings and allow movement between them</li>
    <li><strong>Rivers:</strong> Some paths follow rivers, which may affect certain actions</li>
    <li><strong>Forests:</strong> The spaces between clearings are forests, where the Wanderer can hide</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h3>Turn Structure</h3>
  <p>Each turn consists of three phases:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Birdsong:</strong> Start-of-turn effects based on your faction</li>
    <li><strong>Daylight:</strong> Take actions to advance your position</li>
    <li><strong>Evening:</strong> Draw cards and score points</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h3>Basic Actions</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Move:</strong> Move warriors from one clearing to an adjacent clearing. You must rule the origin or destination.</li>
    <li><strong>Battle:</strong> Attack another faction in a clearing where you have warriors. Roll dice to determine hits.</li>
    <li><strong>Build:</strong> Place a building in a clearing you rule with an open building slot.</li>
    <li><strong>Recruit:</strong> Add new warriors to clearings based on your faction's rules.</li>
    <li><strong>Craft:</strong> Use cards matching clearings you rule to craft items for victory points.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <h3>Rule &amp; Combat</h3>
  <p>
    A faction <strong>rules</strong> a clearing if they have the most combined warriors and buildings there. 
    Ties mean no one rules.
  </p>
  <p>
    In <strong>combat</strong>, each player rolls a die (0-3). The attacker deals hits equal to the higher 
    roll (max: defender's pieces), and the defender deals hits equal to the lower roll (max: attacker's warriors). 
    Warriors are removed first, then buildings. Removing buildings scores victory points!
  </p>
</div>

